{
  "text": "DGKb, a member of the DGK family, is widely distributed in the brain, particularly in the olfactory bulb, cerebral cortex, striatum, and hippocampus [CITATION_1] . DGKb is mainly expressed in neurons, and its expression rapidly increases after 14 days of age in the rat, which is coincident with synapse formation in the brain [CITATION_2] . In addition, we and other researchers previously demonstrated that DGKb regulates spine formation by regulating lipids, and DGKb knockout (KO) mice show impaired memory [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Furthermore, it was reported that the splice variant at the COOH-terminal of DGKb was related to bipolar disorder [CITATION_5] . These results indicate that DGKb plays an essential role in neurons, and its functions are closely related to neurodegenerative disease and mental diseases.",
